  "prompt": "What are some of the most reactive halogens?",
  "response": "The most reactive halogens are fluorine (F) and chlorine (Cl). Fluorine is the most reactive of all, due to its small size and high electronegativity, which allows it to attract electrons very strongly. Chlorine is also highly reactive, though slightly less so than fluorine. The reactivity of halogens generally decreases as you move down the group in the periodic table, so bromine (Br) and iodine (I) are less reactive than chlorine and fluorine. Astatine (At) is at the bottom of the group and is the least reactive of the halogens.",
